105.body: Dissolves in water to form a gel. The gel slows the rate at which food leaves the stomach and into the small intestine. Traps the nutrients, such that they diffuse more slowly through the gel towards the intestinal wall. Properties: Fermentable Fermentable Broken down by gut bacteria (in large intestine). The by-products can nourish colon cells and reduce inflammation. Prebiotic Soluble fibers are generally considered prebiotic because they promote the growth of beneficial intestinal microorganisms. Examples: Inulin â€” potent prebiotic Fructooligosaccharides (FOS) â€” potent prebiotic; food sources often overlap with inulin Galactooligosaccharides (GOS) â€” potent prebiotic; may cause bloatedness Beta-glucan â€” prebiotic; mild potency; has cholesterol-lowering effect [1] Pectin â€” mild potency prebiotic; some bacteria can ferment; helps with stool consistency Psyllium â€” pporly fermented

180.body: Very Low-Density Lipoprotein Key structural protein: ApoB-100 Lipoprotein lipase (LPL) on capillaries, especially in adipose and muscle tissue, hydrolyse the triglycerides. THe fatty acids go into tissues for storage or energy. As VLDL loses triglycerides, it becomes IDL (Intermediate-Density Lipoprotein), then eventually LDL, which delivers cholesterol to cells.
180.title: VLDL

181.body: High-Density Lipoprotein Precursor: ApoA1 The ApoA1 Binds to ABCA1 transporter of cells, which will trigger movement of cholesterol from cell to HDL Activates LCAT, which converts cholesterol into cholesteryl ester (more hydrophobic), which will result move the cholesterol to the core of the HDL particle Interacts with VLDL/LDL by exchanging cholesteryl esters for triglycerides via CETP. Tip EPA and DHA (Omega-3 fatty acids) increase the expression of ABCA1 and ABCG1 genes in cells, which means more cholesterol is pumped out to HDL.
181.title: HDL

183.body: Lipoprotein Lipase LPL is bound to blood vessels in the wall instead of in circulation. LPL hydrolyses triglycerides in VLDL and chylomicrons, releasing FFAs and glycerol . Note Some studies have shown that unsaturated fats increase LPL activity than saturated fats. In other words, it's easier for the body to break down unsaturated fats.

22.body: Why is fried food so bad? Fat oxidation â€” lipid peroxides, aldehydes, trans fat can increase oxidative stress Calorie dense â€” Because of oil absorption especially with batter Advanced Glycation End Products â€” Frying causes proteins and sugars in food to react, forming AGEs. Low in nutrients (because of refined oil) â€” decrease in neutralisation of ROS Reuse â€” oil in deep fried foods are usually reused, increase fat oxidation How is oil refined? Extract (high heat, oxygen) Degum (?) Neutralise Bleach â€” to remove colour Deodorise â€” high heat Hydrogenate â€” increase shelf life Why is refining oils not so great? May contain oxidised PUFAs Strips natural antioxidants like Vitamin E May contain residual solvents Warning 10 minutes of deep frying reduces concentration of linoleic acid by 20%, indicating heavy oxidation. In reused frying oils, oxidation products can rise by 200â€“300% compared to fresh oil.

69.body: PUFAs are sensitive to heat, light, and oxygen. PUFA + O2 -> Oxidised PUFA + lipid peroxides + aldehydes (like 4-HNE, MDA) + free radicals Vitamin E in foods Vitamin E, found in almonds and walnuts etc. acts as a potent antioxidant that protect the PUFA from oxidation. Insulin resistance Lipid peroxides can generate ROS upon degradation. ROS impairs insulin pathways in muscle and liver cells. Genotoxic, cytotoxic 4-HNE and MDA can form adducts with DNA and proteins, which may lead to mutations, cell dysfunction, and even cancer in the long term .
